Inflation in Europe has slipped on food
Accelerated inflation, measured in the euro area, is mainly due to the rapid increase in food prices.
In November, price increases in the 13 eurozone countries were larger than expected, after an inflation rate of 2.6 percent in October, annual inflation of 3.1 percent was recorded, said the statistical office of the European Community in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts indicated only 3 percent, Bloomberg reported.
Unlike the US, UK and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) did not lower the key interest rate, saying that falling interest rates, together with rising commodity prices and falling unemployment rates, would lead to the generation of an inflationary spiral.
The ECB would like to keep the inflation rate below but close to two percent.
According to one analyst, this is Catch 22 for the ECB: "we must dissuade" inflation so that we no longer have to intervene on this subject later.
In Germany, the inflation rate of 3.3 percent is a record in the last twelve years and in Spain it has risen from 3.6 to 4.1.
Inflation in the euro area has taken off due to rapidly rising food and energy prices.
Cereal futures market prices rose 88 percent and soybean prices also reached their highest value since 1973.
The price of edible oil and dairy products also increased significantly in 2007.
This year, the global price of oil has risen by 52 percent, and last month a barrel of oil cost almost $100.
According to the ECB, in 2008 the inflation rate will rise from 2.1 per cent this year to 2.5 per cent, but in 2009 it will fall to 1.9.
According to analysts, the 12-month inflation rate remains around 3 percent, however, in the next 3 to 4 months, the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to cut the key interest rate twice in 2008.
Gallup reports a government crisis
After a long stagnation, the number of supporters of Fidesz (Alliance of Young Democrats) increased significantly at the beginning of December. Since 2002, he now has the largest number of supporters, while Gallup has never before seen such low socialist support, at 13 percent.
For loyal voters, the difference would represent, due to the greater determination of opposition voters, support of more than two-thirds (71 percent) against the support of one-fifth (20 percent) for the MSZP (Hungarian Socialist Party).
According to the poll, the MDF (Forum of Hungarian Democrats) and the SZDSZ (Alliance of Free Democrats) are below the threshold of parliamentarians: their support is two percent among the entire population.
Of the voters loyal to vote, the number of supporters of both parties increased by 1 percent.
The economic climate has continued to deteriorate from the previous low, the proportion of those who considered the country's economic situation to be particularly serious has never been higher, it stands at 41 per cent and according to a further 46 per cent the situation is quite serious.
After the more optimistic outlook of last spring and summer, families are once again more pessimistic about their financial situation.
For next year, the majority of the population expects a worsening and only a tenth predicts an improvement in the situation.
Last December, 71 percent of those surveyed, a majority never seen in previous Gallup polls, felt the prime minister was doing his job rather badly than well.
13 percent of respondents have confidence or a lot of confidence in Ferenc Gyurcsány while 38 percent support Viktor Orbán.
54 percent do not trust the prime minister at all and 27 percent the president of Fidesz.
One indicator of the change in the political situation is the proportion of society that thinks that dissatisfaction with the Prime Minister can be addressed without a change of government.
While after last October's riots, 35 per cent of respondents wanted the government and the prime minister to remain in office, currently the rate is only 20 per cent. The relative majority (33 per cent) believe that holding new elections would be the solution to this situation.
When asked about voting intention, 60 percent of respondents said they would definitely vote and the 20 percent said they would probably vote.
To make the comparison, for a "parliamentary election to be held next Sunday", only 55 percent of respondents would certainly participate and 15 percent complementary would probably participate. According to current intentions, the result of the referendum would be beyond doubt.
74 per cent of people would say no to higher education fees, 79 per cent would say no to consultation fees and 84 per cent would say no to hospital fees.
When we look only at the same proportions among those who expressed their intention to vote in the referendum, respectively 81, 84 and 89 per cent of voters would reject the introduction of registration fees, consultation fees and hospital stay fees.
Auchan is the most expensive, Tesco has increased its prices by almost twenty percent
Hypermarkets in the Budaörs shopping triangle maintained last year's average price increase of 16 percent, with the difference that this year the VAT rate did not increase.
Article by Napi Gazdaság (Daily Economy)
This year, in the Budaörs shopping triangle, the usual daily Christmas Basket also increased by 16 percent on average, with an increase in value well over a thousand forints in all hypermarkets.
Prices, "which had already soared" in large food stores last December, have not risen sharply compared to the previous high base.
Nevertheless, consumers are obviously shocked to see that items purchased well below nine thousand forints last year now cost more than ten thousand forints.
The Daily Basket in the hypermarkets surveyed exceeded the psychological threshold of ten thousand forints by at least 91 forints.
And the highest value of the basket was 10,573 forints.
(In 2003, this value was HUF 6,800.)
Prices for Unicum and live fish remained close to last year's level, but prices for turkey fillet, walnuts and poppies rose sharply.
In the shops, the price of flour and bread followed the data of the KSH (Central Institute of Statistics) but, at Auchan, we found bread of one kilo at only 139 forints.
Competition has not lowered the price of the product below HUF 200.
It was astonishing to see, also in this hypermarket, that the price of a two-litre returnable bottle of Coca-Cola was below 200 forints, so it cost only 257 forints per returnable bottle included.
It only prevents this year, in terms of daily basket, Auchan was the most expensive and Cora the cheapest.
According to our calculations, Cora increased the price of its Daily Basket by 15 percent while Tesco and Auchan increased them by about 18 percent and 18 percent respectively.
Comparing last year's most expensive basket and this year's cheapest basket, we see a gap of 12 percent while the difference between last year's cheapest and this year's most expensive is 21 percent.
Prices increased by an average of 1,480 forints.
Last year, prices increased by an average of 1,206 forints, although the impact of the increase in the VAT rate was already noticeable in last year's Christmas prices.
This process puzzled trade, hypermarkets could not visibly determine what margin to apply on products as they were unable to predict the impact of price changes on consumption.
(If a trader miscalculates the turnover of a product, he risks losing a large profit on the margin adapted to the intensity of the trade.)
Because of the change in the VAT rate, the increase in the prices of the Daily Basket has evolved so excessively that the most expensive basket was 1,720 forints higher than in 2006 while the difference between the cheapest baskets was only 844 forints.
This year, the difference was not so excessive since the value of the most expensive basket was 1,630 forints higher than last year and the prices of the cheapest one increased by 1,284 forints as well.
Bringing the two Christmas seasons closer together, we have seen a catastrophic increase in prices, in less than 20 months the prices of daily consumer items have increased by more than 30 percent in hypermarkets.
(This does not necessarily confirm KSH's data: for some essential power supplies, the statistics institute found a price increase of more than 30 percent in 12 months.
This is the case, for example, with flour and eggs.)
According to the latter's Daily Basket, this seems almost absurd since the price level of this product, already very expensive last year, has increased by just over 10 percent compared to the baseline.
According to the indices, flour suppliers occupy a stronger position than egg suppliers because they have managed to get the sharp price increase accepted by multinationals as well.
In the commercial golden triangle, hypermarkets do not complain, they constantly record good years.
In our experience, the majority of customers no longer look at prices in the three hypermarkets visited.
They buy everything in quantity, they take the shelf-stable food by pallets.
On Wednesday morning, large queues formed at the checkouts of the three hypermarkets as the number of customers increased sharply.
However, according to our information, the turnover is lower in the provinces, many multinationals complain to the survey companies that they do not even reach the expected turnover, not only for food but also for sustainable consumer items.
Many hospitals save on disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand infections, caused mainly by the incorrect use of antibiotics, were recorded in hospitals.
The hygienic conditions of hospitals, the insufficient number of beds, the overwork of medical staff do not help to block infections, says the chief doctor of the National Center for Epidemiology.
Many hospitals also save on disinfectants
Not long ago an MRSA infection was diagnosed in the trauma department of János Hospital.
The antibiotic-resistant bacterium was detected in a man hospitalized following a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year a similar infection occurred in the same place.
The injured man in a serious car accident was discharged from the hospital but shortly afterwards he had to return because of an MRSA infection and, since then, doctors have not been able to perform a major operation on him because of the bacteria in his system.
As of December 10 this year, 1,094 hospital infections caused by a multidrug-resistant pathogen have been reported to the National Nosocomial Surveillance System, said Karolina Böröcz, chief medical officer of the National Epidemiology Center.
Namely that it is the number of infections caused by a multidrug-resistant pathogen that has actually been recorded in hospitals and for the rest we have no information.
About two-thirds of infections (683 infections) were caused by MRSA, i.e. methicillin-oxacillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus.
One-third of people carry Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria in their noses without developing a disease.
Infections caused by AS (such as tonsillitis, tonsillitis, skin infections, traumatic infections) respond well to antibiotics, they are easily curable.
However, if antibiotics are used excessively or inappropriately, the bacteria, which responds well to antibiotics, will develop a bacterium that is well resistant to antibiotics that will grow rapidly in poor hospital conditions.
In case of temporary or prolonged malfunction of the immune system, this bacterium can cause serious hospital infections, such as traumatic infection or sepsis, in elderly patients, of low weight or with a weakened organism.
According to the director of Hospital János, there is nothing special about MRSA infections, these infections are part of the daily life of hospitals.
The infection should not be confused with the epidemic, MRSA is not found only there or we do not look for them, said Tibor Nyulasi.
AS is resistant to antibiotics.
"These patients are isolated, health workers put on rubber gloves and protective masks and we have suitable antibiotics to treat them," Nyulasi said.
A priori, hospitalized patients are examined if they are carriers of MRSA, however the infection can not always be avoided.
Sample collection is not fashionable
The vast majority of infections caused by MRSA could be prevented, but the current conditions and circumstances in Hungarian hospitals are not favourable to prevent the development and proliferation of multidrug-resistant pathogens, says Karolina Böröcz.
Since this infection occurs mainly in hospitals and seniors' residences, hospitals should monitor inpatients and immediately isolate patients with MRSA.
However, microbiological sampling is not fashionable in Hungarian hospitals.
It should be noted that the National Social Security Fund does not finance these examinations.
Most cases only develop if MRSA infection is detectable on the patient, said the chief physician of the epidemiological center.
The European Union has rigorous recommendations for the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine and there are Hungarian guidelines also for the cure of certain infections and syndromes.
Efforts must be made to ensure that antibiotic therapy is targeted, i.e. microbiological examinations should be carried out to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not always take this into account.
Microbiological sampling is even rarer in outpatient and basic care, Böröcz said.
Many hospitals save on disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA proliferates from one patient to another most often through medical personnel.
It is therefore essential to wash your hands, put on gloves and protective masks. However, significant shortcomings are detected in hospitals also in this area.
MRSAs proliferate through infection transmitted by droplet inhalation and contact. However, due to conditions in Hungarian hospitals, the infected patient cannot always be isolated.
In addition, the rooms are often full, the beds are often too close to each other while in terms of epidemic, the sick should be distant from each other of at least 1.5 meters.
Unfortunately, we also see that hospitals, in difficult financial situations, are saving money on disinfectants, they lack nurses, there are many patients, so the risk of contamination is even greater," said Karolina Böröcz.
According to Karolina Böröcz, in hospitals where preventive measures are observed, the number of infections is demonstrably lower or the proliferation of the pathogen can be blocked.
Government project against MRSA
The treatment of MRSA infection represents exorbitant expenses for the social security funds, which is why this infection is being fought everywhere.
In England, for example, the government has established a program to prevent or reduce the incidence of MRSA.
According to published data, this programme is effective and MRSA infections show a decreasing trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) identifies as one of its priorities the prevention of the incidence of multidrug-resistant pathogens (such as MRSA) as well as the prevention of hospital infections caused by these pathogens.
The commissioner, author of a fatal accident, was not intoxicated
The official report relating to the fatal accident caused by the commissioner of the 22nd arrondissement has been drawn up.
It can be excluded that the commissioner of the 22nd district, resigning from his post since, who ran over a pedestrian causing his death last Tuesday, would have driven drunk or stunned, said Friday Attila Morvai, spokesman for the public prosecutor of the capital after the report was established.
The finding confirmed the first result of the investigation which already found that the former commissioner had not consumed alcohol before getting behind the wheel.
Last Tuesday, the former head of the police station of the 22nd arrondissement ran over a 55-year-old man who was in front of him when he turned, with his personal car, in the street Kossuth Lajos of the 22nd arrondissement. The man wanted to cross the road without going through the crosswalk.
(By the way, the fact that he was crossing the road outside the crosswalk is not a mitigating circumstance, according to the Highway Traffic Act a car that initiates a turn must let pedestrians pass.)
The pedestrian died after being taken to hospital.
Following this accident, the commissioner resigned from his post and asked for his retirement because, according to the police communication, this accident upset him a lot.
The investigation into this case is being conducted by the Budapest Public Prosecutor's Office.
Attila Morvai also mentioned that the former commissioner cooperated from the beginning with the magistrates in charge of conducting the investigation.
An additional €400 million for infrastructure
Hungarian Finance Minister János Veres and European Investment Bank (EIB) Vice-President Marta Gajecka signed three agreements worth a total of €400 million for a credit line in Budapest on Friday in Budapest to support education, transport and environmental infrastructure and energy.
In 2006, the European Investment Bank (EIB) adopted a budget of EUR 300 million for the Hungarian budgetary financing of transport and environment projects from the Cohesion Fund, for which a credit agreement worth EUR 100 million has already been signed by the parties. This time, the signed contract concerns the use of the remaining €200 million.
The agreement on the EUR 150 million appropriation also concerns the budgetary financing of education-related projects.
The EIB has approved a total of EUR 300 million for Hungary, the remaining EUR 150 million can be used later, following the extension of the credit agreement.
The parties have signed a contract worth 50 million euros for innovation, the state budget will use this envelope primarily in the framework of the research and development project to be carried out at the University of Debrecen.
During the negotiations, the metro line 4 project was also discussed.
The parties agreed that they would discuss the possible modification of the original contract again once Hungary has finalised the details of the metro financing with the EU.
According to János Veres, this could be done in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has provided a total of EUR 8.4 billion to finance 113 projects in Hungary.
The EIB grants its loans according to the interest rate linked to EURIBOR, with a grace period of 8 years and without commitment fees.
Bulgaria, a paradise for the EU real estate market
The evolution of the Bulgarian real estate market is spectacular, the attention of all Europe is turned to this Balkan country little mentioned in the past.
What, or and who buys on this EU market that is always the cheapest but will quickly become expensive?
Analysis of the Bulgarian division of Re/Max.
Currently, in real estate, Bulgaria is undoubtedly the most fashionable target in Eastern Europe with its ski apartments and cheap seaside houses.
In the mountains, the most popular regions are Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa and, by the sea, Albena, the "Golden Sands", the "Sun Coast", the former Sozopol and Nessebar but they are more and more looking for a building in the region of Kavarna and Balcik also.
According to analysts at Re/Max Bulgaria, sooner or later, the central region of the country, namely Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, Triavna, will also arouse the interest of investors and they are also more and more numerous to buy in the cheap corner of Ruse.
Sofia, the capital, also offers attractive opportunities, with retail and office space promising the highest depreciation rate.
Bulgaria is on the best track to become one of the most attractive golf paradises in Europe and thus be a priority destination, after the summer season and the winter season, also in the other two seasons of the year.
More vigilant investors are already buying in large numbers, for example in the corner of Bansko.
According to analysts, people buying a property in Bulgaria are at the same time looking to change their lives, their way of life.
Most buyers are English but others come from France, Belgium, Spain and increasingly Romania.
Maltese and Cypriot investors are also present. On the shores of the Black Sea and in the most famous ski resorts, we traditionally meet a lot of Russian buyers.
Foreign buyers fall into three groups, says Georgij Jankov, regional director of Re/Max Bulgaria.
People who plan to settle buy renovated buildings, at a price varying between 50 and 100 thousand euros, or old dilapidated houses, at a price ranging from 5 to 15 thousand euros, which are then renovated.
The criteria are easy access and communication possibilities, proximity to a large city, shops and in general that of the local doctor.
The second group includes buyers of second homes (since last December, Bulgaria has been cited among the top 10 holiday destinations in Germany).
The third group is composed of commercial investors who buy in the hope of realizing a capital gain in the medium or long term.
The price of buildings in the capital is constantly increasing due to increasing demand.
In the European Union, property prices are the lowest in Bulgaria. However, in the last 5 years, they have increased by 21 percent each year.
The increase in real estate prices essentially exceeds the increase in wages.
Fodor and the Hungarian six percent
According to the communication of Gábor Fodor, Minister of Environment and Water, the meetings of the professionals end on Tuesday, however, on Wednesday, after the official opening, the negotiations of the ministers on the international climate regime after 2012 will continue.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries around the world will discuss the Bali Roadmap, which is supposed to define efforts beyond the Kyoto Protocol's emission reduction period until 2012.
At the moment, lively discussions are taking place on this subject between developing and developed countries.
The United States also indicated that, for the time being, it did not wish to discuss exact figures, while it was ready to sign an agreement on reducing greenhouse gas emissions by 25 to 40 per cent below 1990 levels by 2020.
Another important topic of the conference is to see if developed countries commit, apart from reducing emissions, to provide financial and technological assistance to countries that need it.
An agreement was also signed on aid to be provided to developing countries.
The aid fund defined by the Kyoto Protocol will be managed by a 16-member board of directors, probably within the framework of the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF), Piac és Profit (Market and Profit) reported.
Hungary's six percent
On behalf of Hungary, Gábor Fodor, Minister of Environment and Water, confirms the EU's ambition to maintain its role as flagship in global efforts to protect the climate and to encourage the signing of the new international agreement before 2009.
The Minister explained that the EU is committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 2020 by 2020 compared to the level reached in 1990, regardless of the successful signing of the "Post-2012 Agreement", and is ready to reduce them by up to 30% if other major regions of the world and/or developing countries are also ready to make commitments. adapted to their responsibility and abilities.
Gábor Fodor recalled that in 1997, the signatory countries of the Kyoto Protocol had targeted a total reduction of 5.2 per cent and all 15 EU members at that time made the commitment on 8 per cent less.
Hungary has made the commitment to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6 percent compared to the level of the period between 1985 and 1987, our country will fulfill its commitment, recalls the press release of the Ministry of the Environment.
The stakes are high in Bali because the long-term international agreement on climate policy must be put in place within two years, otherwise the entry into force of the agreement would certainly be postponed until after 2012. In this case, reduction commitments below the Kyoto Protocol values would not be immediately followed by a new international emission reduction system, the need for which has been highlighted in the new report by IPCC, the international scientific body, which won the UN Nobel Peace Prize on climate change.
The reduction of emissions would be delayed and the increase in the average temperature of the Earth of more than 2 degrees Celsius could no longer be avoided, which, according to scientists, would have extremely serious and irrevocable consequences.
British Army recruits on YouTube
British Army units share recordings made during its operations in Iraq and Afghanistan on the video-sharing site in order to make themselves popular.
First, it was the British Air Force (RAF) that became passionate about YouTube: special units operating in Afghanistan upload video footage of operations against the Taliban since March 2006, the BBC announced.
These recordings, taken using miniature helmet-mounted cameras, are checked at Air Force Operations Headquarters in Kandahar and then transferred to London where compatriots upload them to the Internet.
The political message is inescapable
The soldiers of the air force have already passed 139 sequences on the net by this way and their "channel" has been watched by more than 75 thousand people.
The British Ministry of Defence registered as "defenceheadquarters" in the spring of 2007 and provides videos on operations in Iraq and Afghanistan, while the Commonwealth Office and the International Peacekeeping Forces in Iraq (MNFI) also have their own YouTube channels.
Mission to Afghanistan
According to the initial purpose of the air force, the videos were passed on the net to recruit. According to the Ministry of Defence, they also served to make known to the general public the real objectives of the army's presence abroad.
The propaganda published through this channel costs virtually nothing compared to the usual recruitment advertisements on television, Gordon Mackenzie, a defence consultant, told the BBC. On the other hand, it also inevitably carries a political message since it justifies in a special form the merits of the military operations decided by the government.
The Americans made a game
The army is embetted because, apart from carefully composed and censored videos, amateur videos are passed on the sharing site that also present, for example, the death of soldiers: in "official" propaganda films, a little hypocritical, officers do not avoid talking about casualties but they never present the bloody side of the fight.
Moreover, many videos were already on the net presenting the areas of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan that were carried out in real mission, but the British army is only getting excited about the loading of these videos recently.
Americans recruit a little differently using the free downloadable shootout game America's Army. In this game the player can put himself directly in the place of the soldiers in a more or less real simulation.
