The treacherous trader risked billions because of his inferiority complex
A concealing fraudster.
So designates his former employee, the French giant Société Générale, owner of the Czech bank Komerční banka.
The bank lost nearly five billion euros because of him.
But it seems rather that Kerviel is only a great player who wanted to equal his colleagues, and who, in addition, can in no way be considered incapable.
Unlike all major banking houses, he recognized in time the crisis of the American mortgage market.
"He is fragile," suggested his superiors who denounced him to the police.
However, if we stick to Kerviel's deposition reported by the French media, including Le Monde, the transactions of this man produced at the end of last year a profit amounting to 1.6 billion euros.
The crisis goes beyond the United States
"All I wanted was to make money for my bank," he said in the statement.
Last summer, he managed to take advantage of the American crisis to earn half a billion euros.
In fact, he sensed the opportunity from the beginning of the year.
Reports began to emerge in February that so-called "sub-prime" mortgages, granted to low-income customers or those who had experienced repayment difficulties in the past, would have problems.
But this crisis is not expected to affect the entire economy.
Kerviel did not believe it and he bet well.
Thus, at the end of the year, its profits amounted to 1.6 billion euros.
