Throughout the interrogation, he admits to having falsified the reports in order not to be detected.
He managed to fool his superiors, although the Eurex exchange began to take an interest in his transactions.
Who risks nothing has nothing
Was he afraid of being discovered?
Quite not.
"I felt that just getting $1.6 billion for the bank would satisfy them."
Where does his willingness to risk so big come from?
He only came to his post gradually.
He started working at Société Générale in 2000 just after finishing his studies at the University of Lyon.
His annual salary was around 51 thousand dollars.
Two years later, he was already a trader's assistant, and in 2005 he became a freelance trader with an annual salary of 90 thousand dollars.
Yet he knew he would never earn as much as others.
"From my first interview in 2005, I knew that I was much less regarded than others.
In view of my university curriculum and my professional and personal background," Kerviel told investigators.
However, shortly after taking office, he achieved his first great success.
Thanks to Allianz shares, he earned half a billion euros by betting on the decline of this stock during the London attacks.
And the mechanism was triggered - he wanted more.
As long as you win, we leave you in peace
"There was like a snowball effect," he told police.
But the superiors knew everything, or rather, they suspected it.
"As long as I won, they pretended to close their eyes."
However, it is then that the blow of the beginning of the year comes.
It loses a billion euros in one day.
In mid-January, after the weekend, he decided to hide the sum.
On Monday, when he arrives at work, he is no longer an employee of the bank.
A few days later, the bank announced that it had lost 5 billion euros because of him.
And how was it discovered?
He became suspicious because of his leave.
"Last year, I only took 4 days off.
