Banks want to solve the crisis
The US Federal Reserve Bank, the European Central Bank and the English, Swiss and Canadian central banks have decided to fight the financial market crisis together.
More than one hundred billion dollars will be placed on the money markets through auctions.
It will be for the banks to sell, through an auction system, the interest rates at which they are willing to borrow money.
For example, the US Fed will auction $40 billion and, in addition, it will provide $24 billion to the European and Swiss central banks.
This is the first time since the attacks of the 11th. September that the central banks of individual states have decided on such concerted action, aimed at preventing or even reducing the effects of the financial crisis.
"This approach tends to solve the major problems of the economy, namely the growing lack of free capital that banks could lend," wrote Bernard Baumohl of the consulting firm Economic Outlook Group in his report to clients.
"Concerted action by central banks has lowered the probability of a recession in the United States from 65 percent to about 50 percent," Baumohl said in his report.
Banks have already lost $60 billion to defaulted loans, mostly in the United States.
Analysts expect more losses in the billions.
"Central banks have chosen this approach because they need to really understand what may still follow," said NBA chief economist Amro Kieran Davies.
"It seems that the situation is really bad," he adds.
Central banks fear that, if the banks themselves have difficult access to loans, they will lend more expensive to their customers.
This would reduce consumption and plunge the U.S. economy into a recession that could affect economic growth around the world.
Central banks made this choice after the London interbank rate, called LIBOR, used to borrow on the interbank market, failed to be lowered.
This meant that banks were still afraid of mutual borrowing, despite the fact that the US, Canadian and British central banks had cut interest rates several times during the autumn.
"This will have the same effect as a further cut in interest rates," Greg Salvaggio of Tempus Consulting told Reuters.
