Cuba, the most beautiful island in the Caribbean
For visitors, it is truly an island of freedom.
Everything you expect from your holidays can be achieved if you make a good choice.
Golden and white beaches like snow, high waves or a calm sea like a pond.
Fins and all inclusive with waiters offering you on the beach a pizza, ice cream or intoxicating cocktails.
Kitesurfing, golf and roulette.
On the islands of the Caribbean Sea, you will not find this list only in its entirety, but enriched.
However, there is only one island on which you will find much more and that is Cuba, the largest and most beautiful island in the Greater Antilles.
In the time of the Spanish, Cuba had been the stronghold of their invasion of America.
Christopher Columbus called it the most beautiful place the human eye has ever seen.
Havana became the repository and transshipment of the treasures that the Spanish had stolen and transported to Europe.
Then came the American era.
The Hotel Nacional was built in the early 20's.
It was Lucky Luciano, one of the leaders of the American mafia, who had it built, since everything that was a crime in the USA (especially under prohibition) was admitted and supported in Cuba: drugs, gambling, prostitution.
Among his clients, there were, among others,
Winston Churchill, Ava Gardner, Frank Sinatra.
In Havana, tall buildings grew and cars, belonging to the cult symbols of the 50's of the last century, circulated on the wide boulevards.
Ernest Hemingway bought a property in San Francisco de Paula, near Havana, and in Cojímar he had his yacht.
Stars of show business and politicians from all over America left their signatures on the walls of the Bodeguita del Medio.
So what about today?
You can leave your own autograph on the walls of the Bodeguita de la Havana.
In the bar of the Hotel Nacional, a luxury hotel, you will be mixed the cocktail of your choice.
And these cult cars still circulate in Havana, since the jigoulis and fiats once imported have already for a long time, in a climate so salty and humid, rotten.
Although Havana, especially the oldest part, is noticeably decrepit, nowhere else in the vicinity are there as many splendid colonial monuments as there are precisely there.
Other places become more beautiful, for example Trinidad.
Since tourism brings the money so needed, its development has the green light.
In the last fifteen years, new hotels have sprung up not only in Havana, but especially in Varader, on the coast of Holguín province, and also on small islands such as Cayo Coco, Cayo Guillermo and others.
Cuba still offers a fantasy that is unique in the world and that will be appreciated especially by lovers of small trains.
The cane had returned from the plantations spread out in the sugar factories on a narrow gauge by small steam and motor trains.
Their rolling stock has not been renewed for decades and this is how we can see in operation small locomotives whose contemporaries are elsewhere only in museums.
Where to direct his steps?
The majority of visitors do not miss the most famous places.
There is therefore no need to write a lot about Varadero or Havana.
Otherwise remember that in the property of Hemingway, already mentioned, there is a museum and that whoever loves this writer should not miss the visit.
The Viňales Valley in the west of the island is one of the most picturesque corners of Cuba.
Exuberant vegetation grows on calcareous soil.
Mogotes, limestone balloons and rocks rise in candlelight from the bottom of the valley, and, fertile earth having caught in their bowels, even its rotten rocks are covered with a very dense vegetal carpet.
The valley is where probably the best quality Cuban tobacco is grown.
You will be able to meet the final form of this product if you visit one of Havana's cigar factories.
Perhaps someone will also find it interesting that this is where the Chilean episode of Major Zeman was filmed.
Trinidad
Ancient city founded shortly after the Spanish colonized the island.
It was the slave trade and the sugar trade that brought him fame and wealth.
The richness was embodied in the beauty and showcase city character of this small city.
Koloniální španělská architektura,výrazně ovlivněná pozdějšími francouzskými osadníky, se za čtyři staletí téměř nezměnila.
Trinidad, located between the sea and the Escambray mountain range, is a place so remote that even in the 50's of the last century, there was no road that would connect this region with the rest of the country.
This isolation allowed him to stay on the sidelines.
We didn't build anything, and that's why we didn't demolish anything either, everyone was content to have a roof over their heads.
If you have more time in Trinidad than an afternoon, then it is also worth visiting interesting places in the surrounding area, such as Playa Ancón beach or the Sugar Valley.
Then, in the evening, it is customary to go to the Casa de la Música which comes alive after sunset and where the music is muted only in the early morning.
Baracoa
Some refer to this town located in the extreme east of Cuba as the most beautiful on the island.
This opinion is certainly influenced already by the path that leads to it.
The two roads that lead to it from Guantánamo must cross high and rugged mountains and pass through a landscape almost without marks of human activity.
UNESCO has inscribed the eastern reef of Cuba, thanks to its intact landscape, on the World Heritage List.
The best chocolate is made there, in the church, there is the cross of Christopher Columbus (in fact, it was born about a hundred years after the journey of Columbus) and from the hill where the old castle and the current hotel El Castillo stand, you can see several table mountains, the most famous of which is El Yunque.
About coffee, rum, cigars, the Sierra Maestra mountain range, the Bay of Sows and Isla de Pinos Island, the Tropicana cabaret, the sanctuary of the patron saint of Cuba Caridad del Cobre, Santeria, African religions practiced by the descendants of former slaves, about all this we could fill a lot of pages.
Only, as they say, it is better to see once.
In Afghanistan, allies are passive, say Americans
The lack of soldiers and necessary equipment influences, according to the United States, the progress of the mission in Afghanistan.
According to Defense Secretary Robert Gates, NATO should outline a concrete plan for the coming years.
The mission in Afghanistan is not going as it should, agreed in Edinburgh in Scotland representatives of countries that have troops in the southern part of the country.
In addition to growing opposition from the Taliban movement, the eight states involved are now also discussing future plans and allied coordination.
While the United States this week called on NATO troops through Defence Secretary Robert Gates for greater activity, Britain sees strengthening the authority of the Afghan government and stepping up development aid as a priority.
"The evolution in Afghanistan is perceptible, but military might can only be part of the solution.
The other is to allow residents to start a new development of the economy and security themselves," British Defence Minister Des Browne told the BBC.
Ninety percent
Afghan insurgent activity is, according to U.S. military data, the most intense in the past five years.
The number of violent actions increased by 27 percent compared to last year, up to 60 percent in the southern province of Helmand.
NATO countries have about 40,000 troops in Afghanistan, almost a quarter of them in the southern part.
However, according to the United States, the allies have reached their absolute limit both in the organization and equipment of the troops.
Specifically, they are asking for other helicopters, soldiers and experts to train Afghan troops.
"We will have to think seriously about concrete goals for the coming period, as well as how to achieve them," Gates said.
NATO Secretary General Jaap de Hoop made similar remarks today.
"I'm not happy with what we have on land and in the air in Afghanistan.
We have about ninety percent of the troops and equipment we need, and that's not enough," De Hoop told Reuters at the end of talks with the Japanese government in Tokyo that lasted three days.
Who is passive
The last few months have also reigned conflicts between the countries involved over whether all allies are actually doing everything possible in Afghanistan.
For example, Germany has been criticized for its passivity.
"The Germans have a relatively large representation in Afghanistan.
But they are engaged in areas where violence is minimal, so the combat requirements they are subject to are not as stringent as those in the southern and eastern parts of the country where we operate," Gates said.
The British tabloid Sun this week called German soldiers lazy.
"Afghan slackers discovered: Germans play, while ours fight," Sun wrote in a document supplemented by photos of German soldiers playing table-stand.
The German newspaper Bild went on the counter-attack by publishing a photo of a British troop during a rugby match in the southern part of Afghanistan.
State debt to rise to one trillion in 2009
The burden of a state debt exceeding 84,000 crowns falls on each Czech.
The total debt rose to 842.7 billion crowns at the end of September.
The government had planned to borrow 159.2 billion crowns this year.
Thanks to a better-than-expected development of state budget savings, the ministry has reduced the planned amount to 152.8 billion crowns.
The Czech Republic's state debt rose towards the end of September to 842.7 billion crowns.
During the nine months of this year it has therefore increased by 40.2 billion crowns.
However, from June onwards, it decreased by 13.4 billion crowns.
Today, the Ministry of Finance confirmed its data on the State's debt dating from the beginning of October.
The burden of a debt exceeding 84,000 crowns falls on each Czech.
During the whole of last year, the state was indebted by more than 111 billion crowns.
"At the moment, it seems that, thanks to a smaller deficit forecast for next year, we could cross the trillion crown border only in 2009.
Next year, the debt is expected to be between 900 billion and one trillion crowns," Patria Finance analyst David Marek told iHNed.cz.
Next Finance analyst Vladimír Pikor's forecast is similar: "We could exceed one trillion in 2009.
The precise date will depend on the next budget, which we do not yet know.
If it appeared that the situation on the political scene changed, that politicians were ready to save more, the date could be postponed to 2010.
But I don't expect this change," he said.
Debts are growing
The State's debt is constituted by the debts of the central government and it is generated essentially by the accumulation of deficits in the State budget.
The State's debt is financed by treasury bills, annuity securities, direct loans or, for example, by loans from the European Investment Bank.
The State's internal debt has increased this year so far from 38.5 billion to 719.4 billion crowns.
The state's external debt has increased this year so far from 1.7 billion crowns to 123.3 billion crowns.
The so-called tradable state debt reached 803.3 billion crowns at the end of September and from June it decreased by 13.7 billion crowns.
The average liability of the State's debt was 6.5 years.
"Total debt has increased inter-annually from the first to the third quarters by 13 percent, which is, given the current good health of the economy, far too high.
It is interesting that the increase is generated mainly by annuity securities where it reaches 20 per cent.
It is bad that the debt is growing, but on the other hand it indicates that there will be something to negotiate when the pension reform comes," Pikora data commented.
Better than expected
As a result of the strategy for financing and managing the State's debt for 2007, the government had planned to borrow 159.2 billion crowns this year.
However, at the beginning of September, thanks to a better-than-expected evolution of the state budget savings, the ministry reduced the planned amount to 152.8 billion crowns.
The sum is mainly made up of the deficit of the state budget which will obviously reach 76 billion crowns this year, instead of the 91.3 billion crowns initially planned.
Secondly, there are the maximum sources provided for the Czech Consolidation Agency, namely 13.3 billion crowns, the reserve of 10 billion for the payment of pensions, the financing of state annuity securities for 43 billion crowns and the repayments of loans from the European Investment Bank amounting to 1.8 billion crowns.
She was appearing in court in Khartoum today for naming a teddy bear
The British teacher tried in Sudan for insulting Islam was sentenced Thursday night by a Khartoum court to 15 days in prison and deportation, her lawyer said.
The Briton was accused of letting students aged 6 to 7 give the name of Muhammad to a teddy bear when any depiction of the prophet of Islam is illegal.
She was liable to lash.
The 54-year-old British teacher at Unity High School in Khartoum, Sudan, was arrested Sunday at her home and charged with insulting Islam and sedition under Article 125 of Sudan's penal code, following several complaints from parents of students to the Sudanese Ministry of Education.
The story actually goes back to September, when this teacher asks her students, aged 6/7, to choose a name for the teddy bear in the class.
"Eight names come out of the mouths of the children, including Hassan, Abdullah and Mohammed," says the school's principal Robert Boulos.
Finally, after a vote in the class, 20 out of 23 children chose Mohamed as their preferred name.
Mohamed is of course the name of the Muslim prophet, but above all a very common name in Sudan.
The children then made a book for the class with the photo of the bear followed by the caption "My name is Mohamed".
The bear itself had no label with this name, but the problem is simply that of the depiction of the prophet as an insult to Islam.
One of Gillian Gibbons' Muslim colleagues, a teacher at the same school in Sudan, said he knew her well and that she would never have done anything insulting to a religious faith, "I just regret that she asked the children to vote for a name", which he said was only an "innocent mistake".
This opinion is shared by many of the teacher's students who describe her as "very attentive to her students" and "who never talks about religion in class".
Remember that the name Mohamed is also the second name most given in Great Britain, it is written in English in 14 different ways.
This name often chosen by Muslim families is a way of honoring the prophet (often given to the first child of a family).
But what are the rules regarding the use of this name?
For example, can it be given to a toy?
This is, of course, a matter of interpretation.
They failed to reach an agreement on the province's future status on Wednesday at the latest negotiating session in Vienna.
In the end, failure.
Kosovo Serbs and Albanians concluded a sixth and final session of talks Wednesday morning in Baden, Austria, without having been able to overcome their differences over the future status of the breakaway province.
"It is regrettable that the parties were not able to reach an agreement on the status," European Ombudsman Wolfgang Ischinger told a press conference in Vienna.
Stressing that peace in the region was "at stake", his US counterpart, Frank Wisner, urged Belgrade and Pristina to respect their commitments to preserve peace and dialogue beyond the end of negotiations.
"Violence is not expected in the immediate future but we are entering a very difficult period," he added, noting that "obvious tensions exist".
End of mediation on December 10
The mediators of the troika, which includes the European Union, the United States and Russia, will visit Serbia and Kosovo for the last time on Monday.
The future of the 90 percent Albanian-speaking province could become clearer when Ischinger, Wisner and Russian mediator Alexander Botsane-Khartchenko submit their report to the UN Security Council by Dec. 10.
The talks in Baden, near Vienna, were the sixth and final round of negotiations since the troika was tasked with a new UN mediation last August.
Americans and Europeans consider that their mediation will end on 10 December.
The Russians, who have already blocked the granting of independence to Kosovo in the Security Council, insist on continuing negotiations beyond this deadline.
"Russia was and remains committed to a negotiated solution, a compromise solution," Botsane-Khartchenko said.
Unilateral declaration of independence?
After eight years of UN administration of Kosovo, the West believes that independence under EU supervision is the only viable solution.
Pristina says it is ready to proclaim it unilaterally if the Security Council does not decide in its favour.
Belgrade insists on increased autonomy.
"Unfortunately, no agreement has been reached," announced the president of the autonomous authority of Kosovo, Fatmir Sejdiu, in the hotel of Baden where were taking place since Monday these "negotiations of the last chance".
Hashim Thaci, former commander of the Kosovar rebellion and future prime minister of the province, expressed regret.
But he added that the autonomy plan presented by Belgrade "belonged to a past that led to murders and deportations."
'Domino effect'
Serbian President Boris Tadic said a compromise was still possible, warning Kosovo's Albanian majority of the consequences of unilaterally declaring the province's independence.
Belgrade says it fears a "domino effect" in a region still weakened by the wars of independence in the 1990s.
"For Serbia," he said, "this does not mean that a compromise is impossible."
On Tuesday, the Serbian delegation insisted that any decision should be taken exclusively by the Security Council, where its Russian ally has veto power.
'Kosovo's Parliament will have the last word'
"Only a solution in the Security Council is acceptable to Serbia," Serbian Prime Minister Vojislav Kostunica said.
"These negotiations lasted two years.
They must end as they began: in the Security Council."
To journalists, Fatmir Sedjiu replied that "the Parliament of Kosovo will have the last word on the status", adding that any unilateral declaration of independence by Albanian speakers would be done "in consultation" with the West.
