Speaking after the US president, Abbas insisted that the upcoming negotiations be "comprehensive and thorough" and cover all aspects of a settlement, citing "Jerusalem, refugees, borders, settlements, water, security, among others."
Olmert pledged that the upcoming talks would be "direct and continuous" and to make "an effort to complete them in the course of 2008".
Bush has set the end of 2008 as the deadline for implementing his "vision of two states" of Palestine and Israel that coexist.
Saudi Arabia revealed that it had obtained a commitment to this effect from Bush before deciding to participate in the conference.
Saudi Arabia, whose participation in Annapolis was a success for Washington, was behind a plan, endorsed by all Arab countries, that offered Israel peace in exchange for its withdrawal from all Arab territories occupied during the 1967 war, including East Jerusalem.
