Spectacular repair on the space station
It took astronaut Scott Parazynski and his International Space Station (ISS) crew more than seven hours of work in space to make the dramatic repair of a torn solar panel, essential to the station's continued scientific activities.
A risky exit that has accumulated records because of its duration, its distance from the habitable modules, the speed with which it was imagined, the tools "cobbled together" by the astronauts to carry out the repair.
The problem emerged on Tuesday when astronauts unloaded the Harmony module, a large cylindrical piece that would soon house the European and Japanese science laboratories, from the Discovery shuttle (see box).
This module is a kind of landing dock for laboratory modules.
But you have to be able to supply them with electricity.
The second task of the crew was therefore to move a module of electricity production by solar panels weighing 17.5 tons, already present on the ISS, in order to put it in position on its final position.
After moving it, the crew began redeploying the module's solar panels, which have a wingspan of 76 meters.
And that's where one of the panels, which unfold like accordions, was damaged for nearly a meter by a cable that got stuck.
The deployment was stopped so as not to further damage the panel.
The astronauts, who were originally supposed to perform a control sortie of the shuttle Discovery, and then go to repair another solar panel whose rotation system was defective, were forced to devote themselves to the damaged panel.
And it was Scott Parazynski who was chosen to caracolate at the end of the 30 meters of length of the remote-controlled arm of the shuttle added to that of the station to carry out the repair.
He is one of NASA's best spacewalkers.
Tall, resistant, very dexterous, he has a very developed torso and long arms.
At the age of 46, this doctor by training was therefore tasked with "operating" the "injured" solar panel.
After precisely inspecting the damage, he severed the offending cable and installed some sort of "splints" on the damaged area.
He was helped by a second "spacewalker" who remained near the airlock and, from the inside, by the other astronauts including Peggy Whitson, the crew commander.
The tool he used, a mini-hockey cane wrapped in insulation to prevent electrocution on solar panels producing several hundred volts, was designed and "tinkered" by astronauts aboard the station.
Once the operation was complete, Scott Parazynski waited until the panel was fully deployed before taking inventory of his tools and returning to the interior of the station.
Yesterday afternoon, the astronauts enjoyed a half-day of relaxation before today, seven astronauts returned to the shuttle Discovery for a return to Earth scheduled for Wednesday.
