A heavy memory
After more than 60 years of confidentiality, the Nazi archives in Bad Arolsen, which trace the fates of 17.5 million victims of Hitler's regime, are freely accessible.
The 47 million archival documents, stored on 27 km of linear in Bad Arolsen (Hesse), were until now only available for "humanitarian" purposes, i.e. individually and nominatively, at the request of a former victim or his beneficiaries.
The eleven states in charge of their management - including Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May 2006 to open them to researchers and historians.
The process of ratification of this agreement by all States having been completed, the opening has been effective since yesterday.
Sensitive information
Historians' access to Bad Arolsen will allow research "including on the movements of prisoners, the population of the camps and the state of health of forced labourers," said Reto Meistern, director of the archives, which are run by the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, several States, including Germany, opposed the opening to the public of these nominative documents, because of the sensitive nature of certain information.
Like the supposed homosexuality or mental disability of some victims of deportation.
Concentration camp registers or arrest warrants issued by the Gestapo had been collected after the war for a practical purpose: to find civilians deported or subjected to compulsory labour and, possibly, to provide them with proof of their internment, in order to pave the way for their compensation.
Even today in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees process tens of thousands of individual applications.
However, for part of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited interest.
"There is nothing fundamentally new to expect from these documents," Prof. Wolfgang Benz, director of the Center for Research on Antisemitism at the Technische Universität Berlin, said in 2006.
