Bank of England acknowledges concerns by offering £10 billion over five weeks
The Bank of England said Thursday it was anxious to ease the current return of concerns about credit conditions, and announced an offer of ten billion pounds at the base rate of 5.75% over five weeks, an offer of unusual duration.
"To alleviate concerns that financial market conditions will be particularly tight at the end of the year, and to give banks greater certainty in how they will organise their liquidity positions over this period, the Bank intends to offer a significant proportion of its planned reserve contribution during the maintenance period beginning on 6 December in the form of a five-week open market operation,"  it said in a statement.
The bank specifies that 10 billion pounds (14 billion euros) will be put on the market on December 6 at 12:15 GMT, at the base rate and until January 10.
This is the first time the BoE has put five-week liquidity on the market in an open market operation.
These are normally done within a week.
The BoE added in its statement that it "stands ready to take further steps to maintain rates" of overnight interbank lending in line with its base rate.
The overnight interbank rate was 5.829% on Wednesday.
The three-month rate stood at 6.6%, the highest since September 18.
Since the beginning of the financial crisis in the summer, the sums put on the market by the Bank of England were accompanied by a significant penalty rate that had deterred banks from using them.
According to some rumours, corroborated by the evolution of the pound's exchange rate against the euro, many had preferred to subscribe to the sums put on the market by the European Central Bank, at more advantageous rates and with more assured discretion.
