Following numerous rumors about C3 Presents' creation of a new music festival in Philadelphia, the promoter/producer announced the Vineland Music Festival in New Jersey, in partnership with British producer Melvin Benn's Festival Republic.
"For our company, it's an honor to work with someone who has inspired the current festival movement in America," C3's Charlie Jones told Billboard.com.
C3 produces Chicago's Lollapalooza Festival and the Austin City Limits Music Festival.
Vineland, New Jersey is a summer camping destination.
The festival is scheduled to be held Aug. 8-10 on a 500-acre private farm about 40 minutes from Philadelphia.
Once known as Mean Fiddler, Festival Republic director Melvin Benn is one of the world's most respected festival producers.
In 1989, he took the helm of the Reading Festival in the United Kingdom, which attracts some 80,000 people annually.
In 1999, Melvin Benn added the Leeds Festival to his portfolio and in 2006, Festival Republic established the Latitude Festival in Henham Park, Suffolk.
Since 2002, as co-owner, Melvin Benn has also been responsible for the production, licensing and organizational tasks of the Glastonbury Festival, which now seats up to 177,500 people.
Calling Glastonbury "the most inspiring event" he's ever attended, C3's Charlie Jones says his company and Melvin Benn's are working in parallel to give the region a European-style festival-event.
"We chose Philadelphia as our market and were working diligently with the Fairmount Parks Commission to create a festival in downtown Philadelphia," Jones said.
"We were in talks with the city and the Commission was motivated and excited about this project.
Unfortunately, we have become bogged down in politics because of the current administration," Jones said.
"Fortunately, we were able to speak with Melvin Benn and we are about to create a great festival at an exceptional site that will ultimately serve the people of Philadelphia."
C3 Presents resurrected the Lollapalooza festival in 2005 at Chicago's Grant Park, after making a name for itself in the festival landscape in 2002 with the Austin City Limits Music Festival.
The two events recorded gross revenues of $9.8M and $11.3M respectively in 2007.
Both festivals are held in urban areas.
"Melvin Benn's European model is a country festival, while ours are more in urban green spaces," says Charlie Jones.
The aim is to merge, in one way or another, the two formulas to give both a European and an American-style urban festival feel."
Vineland is about halfway between Philadelphia and Atlantic City.
"The community of Vineland, including the mayor, enthusiastically supports this event," says Charlie Jones.
The latter refuses to reveal the terms of the agreement, but says "they are interesting enough to invest in such an event and host a festival that will hopefully have a long life."
Charlie Jones says the capacity of this festival is "very large," as is that of 80,000 people at the Bonnaroo Music Festival in Tennessee.
He said invitations had been extended to the groups, but nothing could yet be confirmed at the time of going to press.
"Vineland will be rock-flavored, but the music will be varied, hoping to attract all kinds of spectators," says Charlie Jones.
His partners at C3, which received the Top Independent Promoter award at the last Billboard Touring Awards, are Charlie Walker and Charles Attal.
