Will there be an end-of-year rally on the stock market? Experts divided by the sub-prime crisis.
With less than five weeks to go until the end of the fiscal year, investors are already rubbing their hands hoping for the arrival of the traditional end-of-year rally.
However, this year experts are not as sure that will happen.
Banif believes that "from a statistical point of view, the month of December on the stock market generally has a positive behavior.
However, it is not appropriate to make forecasts based exclusively on statistics, since given the current context, uncertainties lie in wait in the markets, at least in the short term."
Although they are not in favour of the stock market gaining momentum in the last weeks of the year, these experts point out that "the stock market feeds on the existence of liquidity, willing to invest given the lack of alternatives with guarantees, especially fixed income, affected by the leakage effect towards quality stocks both in long and short periods".
For this, they believe that the stock market will have a rather lateral behavior, not free of volatility "especially because we do not know the impact of the probable rate cut of the Fed, given the high level of crude and the danger of stimulating inflationary pressures"
Javier Barrio, BPI's sales manager in Spain, agrees that this is not the right time to say there will be a rally.
"It's not the best thing," says the expert.
The Ibex, the Spanish stock index, has lost nearly 4% since November 8 when the index closed at 15,945.7 points.
However, not all experts have this negative view.
Juan Solana, an analyst at Intermoney, believes that the Ibex 35 could close the year at 16,000 points thanks to the reorganization of portfolios and the traditional contributions to pension schemes that occur every year during these dates.
However, the expert nuances that things will be a little different this year since he believes that the rally will take place from the second week of December, after the bridge of the Constitution Day (December 6).
The analyst does not consider that volatility will affect the market trend.
For his part, Federico Olucha, analyst at Inversis Banco, believes that we are close to technical levels and "that is why we could observe a rebound in the index that could be caused depending on the information that arrives from the European Union regarding the consequences of the crisis on the credit market".
The analyst hopes that these will be positive.
Analysts agree on the stocks that will be responsible for leading Ibex to new maximum targets.
Intermoney's Solana says that "this year the big values are back for him".
The expert would include in the portfolio the two big banks and some manufacturers "because when the date approaches, the electricity sector will be very expensive".
Meanwhile, Federico Olucha, of Inversis Banco assures that the increases will be due to the bank and the industrial sector.
Manufacturers will also be able to benefit from this rally, if they get started.
"ACS has been recovering positions for several months and we hope that other manufacturers such as Ferrovial and FCC will follow the same path," said the expert.
Cyclical consumption will be protagonist in the last part of the year due to the increase in sales in the Christmas sales season.
On the other hand, the expert believes that technology companies will also do it very well, although in this case there is not much representation in the Spanish market.
Five times for seven years
In the last seven years, only on two occasions has December been a bearish month.
The real year-end rally took place in 2003, when stock markets emerged from the crisis caused by the bursting of the tech bubble.
This year, during which the Ibex 35 recovered 28.17%, the month of December recorded an increase of 6.68%.
We will have to see if 2007 is the fifth consecutive year of gains (for the moment the Ibex has increased by 8.36% since January) and if it succeeds in computer on its end-of-year rally.
