Now that the U.S. housing market is going through a critical phase, predators are targeting the U.S. credit card market.
Goldman Sachs analysts believe credit card losses could reach $99 billion if the contagion spreads from mortgages to other forms of consumer credit.
Signs of tension are clearly visible.
There are increases in fee and insolvency rates, which measure the shares of the balance sheet that are not or are recoverable more than 30 days later.
HSBC announced last month that it took $1.4 billion in consumer credit, partly because of weak cardholders.
Still, it's too early to panic.
Costs and insolvencies are still moderate.
According to Moody, a tax agency, the insolvency rate of 3.89% in the third quarter is almost one point lower than its historical average.
The deterioration in rates is partly explained by technical factors.
A change in laws in 2005 in the United States, regarding personal bankruptcy caused a precipitous drop in bankruptcy records, which in turn caused heavy losses for credit cards; The number of archives (and therefore insolvency rates) could increase even if borrowing conditions were to worsen.
The industry also announces fixed payment rates, which highlight the amount of monthly debt that consumers must pay.
And confidence in the security of credit card capital is quite strong despite the paralysis of other aspects of structured finance.
Dennis Moroney of TowerGroup, a research firm, predicted that issuance volume for 2007 will be 25% higher than last year.
The direct infection links between the mortgage crisis and the credit card market certainly exist: consumers might prefer to increase their debt loads now that fair mortgages are gone.
But card issuers pay more attention to the flow of cash rather than the value of wealth, and so falling property prices have not necessarily led to a change in borrowers' credibility.
They could even bring benefits to issuers of credit securities.
Consumer premiums for paying mortgages fall if properties cost less than the value of the loan; As a result, credit card debt would become a priority to repay everything.
Card issuers are able to respond much faster than mortgages and with more flexibility to such stress conditions, as they can change interest rates or alter recurrent limits.
This should theoretically reduce the risk of a quick rally in equities.
"We're not going to wake up one morning and revalue all the borrowing," said Gary Perlin, head of Capital One.
If a financial catastrophe of the credit card market is unlikely, there is a high risk of a significant decline.
