But during a hearing presided over by U.S. Judge Ewing Werlein Jr., they all pleaded guilty to fraud.
The three former executives of Greenwich NatWest, a subsidiary of the Royal Bank of Scotland's PLC group, have become famous across Britain because of the two-year extradition proceedings.
In the United States, their case is still an outstanding question for this investigation launched following the fall of Enron in 2001.
The charges against them in 2002 made it clear to Fastow that he was the subject of the government's investigation into the Enron debacle.
The charges against the bankers, dubbed the "Natwest Three" claim to have come to Houston in 2000, to organize a fraudulent scenario with Fastow and his former right-hand man, Michael Kopper.
NatWest Greenwich invested in a subsidiary of an Enron partner controlled by Fastow, who was the director of many fraudulent scenarios, which helped it rig bankruptcy proceedings.
In early 2002, the bank had estimated its interest in the subsidiary as zero, but in fact the three Britons already know its value.
A company controlled by Kopper bought the subsidiary's bank interest for £1 million.
The bankers paid Kopper $250,000 as interest for this company.
According to the accuse, Fastow falsely told Enron that the energy company was willing to pay Greenwich NatWest $20 million for its shares in the subsidiary.
But in truth that $20 million went into the pockets of British bankers, Fastow and others.
According to the charges, the bankers got $7.3 while Fastow, Kopper and the others earned $12.3 million.
In January 2004, Fastow pleaded guilty to his active role in two conspiracies in the Enron debacle.
The British trio was arrested three months later.
Fastow endured a six-year incarceration in a federal prison in Louisiana.
Kopper is incarcerated for 3 years and one month in a prison in Texarkana.
The three Britons were released on bail of $1 million each, forcing them to live in the United States during the trial.
