Venus is Earth's infernal twin.
Despite its atmosphere hostile to life, Venus looks more like Earth than previously believed: the European space probe "Venus Express" has discovered lightning in the atmosphere and swirls of wind at the poles, similar to those that appear in winter on Earth.
For almost three decades, scientists have assumed that there are lightning bolts on Venus.
The European probe "Venus Express" today proved this - it detected electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere: lightning on Venus bursts at a height of about 56 kilometers from cloud to cloud, reports Christopher Russell of the University of California at Los Angeles in the scientific magazine "Nature".
According to the famous theory of cyprin, lightning would have made life appear on Earth: the storm would have stimulated reactions in the oceans that led to the formation of amino acids, cornerstone of life.
This is not the case on Venus: "If there was life, it must have been at a very ancient date in history," says Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
Today there should be hardly any living things on the surface of Venus: the atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on Earth, there are sometimes temperatures of 500 degrees.
"Venus may be Earth's infernal twin, but it's still a twin," Russell said.
Why Venus, which is so similar to Earth in mass and dimensions, was struck by such a different evolution, is the fundamental question of the ESA mission.
The departure of "Venus Express" in November 2005 was an important milestone in the Venusian search, since no probe had been on its way to explore this planet since the nineties.
In the researchers' opinion, the most recent research results that have now been presented in several articles in "Nature" do not only highlight the uniqueness of Venus within the solar system.
They also show that the similarities with the Earth of our neighboring planet are more numerous than assumed at first glance.
Thus, the researchers found, in addition to the wind vortices already known at the North Pole, a whirlwind of clouds at the South Pole, which rotates even faster.
The phenomenon is reminiscent of air currents in the Earth's hemispheres in winter, writes a team of researchers around Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Istituto di Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica.
The second planet of the solar system has almost the same mass as the Earth and is, with a diameter of 12,100 kilometers, almost as large.
The planet known as the evening or morning star revolves around the sun in just 225 days.
However, it turns much more slowly on itself: a Venusian day lasts 243 Earth days.
Although Venus, with surface temperatures of 460 degrees Celsius and a pressure of 92 bar, bears little reminiscent of Earth, scientists speculate that the two planets formed under similar conditions.
Of both, water accumulated and remained on Earth as oceans, but was lost in space on Venus.
And while carbon dioxide has fixed itself on Earth as carbonate, it makes up most of the atmosphere on Venus.
