Right now, wooden crates made in Sweden cast shadows on Warhol's list of works.
Many of the ninety "Stockholm Type" Brillo-Boxes listed there are counterfeiters.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" questioned a few months ago the authenticity of Andy Warhol's Brillo-Boxes of the year 1968, the internal research of the Moderna Museet in Stockholm today leads to a disenchanting result: the six "Brillo-Boxes", which the former director of the museum Pontus Hulten donated in 1995 to the Moderna Museet,  are copies - as well as much of the other hundreds of Brillo-Boxen of "Type Stockholm", which circulate on the international art market.
Ancient history is entangled, a disconcerting sequence of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964, Warhol created in New York his first "Brillo-Boxes", painted wooden boxes, which are based on the red-blue-white design of the "Brillo" powdered soap cartons.
An exhibition of his work at the Moderna Museet in 1968 presented - with Warhol's agreement - hundreds of Brillo boxes made of cardboard: These did not come (for financial reasons) from Warhol, but had been delivered directly from the Brillo cardboard factory.
These were not works of art, but rather their models, exhibition samples.
At the same time, Warhol had given permission in 1968 to have some Brillo wooden crates produced in Sweden, which were not exhibited at the Moderna Museet.
Witnesses of the time speak today of about fifteen wooden boxes that at the time would have entered the history of art and auctions, as original Brillo-Boxes of Andy Wahrol authorized, with the name "Type Stockholm".
Some of them have reached more than $100,000 in auctions.
The problem now is that the legendary museum director Pontus Hultén later claimed that about a hundred wooden crates had been produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, which Warhol would then have ceded to him.
In truth, Hultén's 105 crates were produced in Malmö only in 1990, for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
By then, Warhol had already been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, chief curator of the Moderna Museet, examined three others from private Swedish collections, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968, alongside the museum's six Brillo-Boxes, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968: their laminate panels were first printed and sanded, then white oil paint was applied with a brush.
The texture of the copies, which date from the year 1990, reveals on the contrary that the paint was directly applied without a base layer on the laminate panels, using a paint roller - moreover it is not an oil paint, but an acrylic.
"These crates have not been authorized by the artist and should be removed from Andy Warhol's official list of Brillo-Boxes," suggests Moderna Museet director Lars Nittve: "If the Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board in New York does not come to another decision, the Moderna Museet will classify the six crates in its collection as copies/exhibition material."
Already in July the Authentication Board announced that it would investigate the "heavy accusations" that will be raised in the case of boxes of soap powder.
But since then, there has been an inexorable silence.
Rebel Soldiers in Manila give up
In the Philippines, rebel soldiers are giving up, the same ones who had holed up in a hotel in Manila, and who had demanded the withdrawal of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
Chief Antonio Trillanes, who blamed the president for corruption and electoral fraud, told reporters at the hotel that he could not answer for any bloodshed.
Soldiers loyal to power had stormed the hotel with tear gas shortly before.
The two dozen soldiers had been holed up in the building for hours.
About half of them were standing in court on Wednesday because of a failed coup attempt in 2003 - among them Trillanes.
He took advantage of the audience to suddenly slip away with about 30 supporters.
The military police, who were normally supposed to monitor them, had apparently deserted in his favour and joined his mutiny.
They broke into the Peninsula Hotel and demanded the withdrawal of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
Troops loyal to the government cordoned off the area around the respectable hotel.
The President convened an urgent meeting of the Security Cabinet.
National Security Councilor Norberto Gonzales condemned the soldiers' action.
"People have had enough," Trillanes said.
"We call on people to join us."
Gen. Danilo Lim, who previously commanded the elite Scout Rangers unit, said other army units wanted to join the march soon.
Critics of the regime had called for a large demonstration against the president on Wednesday.
His government has been surrounded for months by accusations of corruption.
Manila's financial district had already been the scene of an attempted mutiny by about 200 members of the army against Arroyo since 2003.
The insurrection broke down nearly 24 hours later when the army refused to join.
Since 1986 there have already been at least seven coup attempts against democratically elected governments in the Philippines.
United Internet becomes a major shareholder of Versatel.
United Internet secured a more than 20 percent stake in telecommunications company Versatel.
The average price per share is 14.46 euros, as communicated by the company on Wednesday.
Only 20.05 per cent of the registered capital would be held.
We had already speculated before on a takeover.
The option would remain open to further increase the stake in Versatel.
With this step we seek to accelerate the consolidation of the German DSL market, United Internet has communicated.
Just before, speculation had already been made on Wednesday about an entry, after Berenberg Bank increased its stake in the Düsseldorf-based network operator from 5 percent to 15.1 percent.
The credit institute would hold the money only for a third part, it is said on the market.
The day before, United Internet had already acquired a nearly 10 percent stake in the mobile phone company Drillisch.
As part of a capital increase, Drillisch placed 17.4 million new shares worth €106.4 million on the stock exchange.
United Internet bought 5.15 million for 31.1 million euros.
In addition, the companies have opened negotiations on cooperation in the marketing of DSL and mobile phone products.
"We are strengthening our partnership," a United Internet spokesperson said.
The two companies founded the joint venture MSP in order to absorb the competitor Freenet.
For now, the two companies want to be satisfied with their ten percent stake in Freenet, and not make use of their right to endorse an additional 18.49 percent in Freenet, United Internet said Thursday.
The two companies would, however, leave all options open, especially to increase the stake in Freenet SA, it was learned.
Negotiations between United Internet and Freenet over a strategic partnership ended in mid-October.
The poker still difficult to predict on Freenet that has been going on for months is part of the consolidation of the German telecom market.
Freenet had 2.9 million mobile customers and 1.27 million DSL customers and full subscriptions at the end of the third quarter.
The holding company of United Internet and Drillisch previously held a direct interest in Freenet of 6.01 percent.
It has now been agreed that Drillisch will contribute about four percent more.
The right to buy the 18.49 percent of the investment company Vatas had already been decided in August.
